  pages={410-414},
  abstract={This paper introduces DeepWS, a dynamic scheduling algorithm that leverages the A2C (Actor-Critic) reinforcement learning algorithm and Graph Convolution Network (GCN) techniques. Unlike existing models, DeepWS does not necessitate prior knowledge of the entire Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG), enhancing scalability and enabling versatility across diverse DAG graphs. Employing reinforcement learning and GCN, DeepWS adeptly adapts task scheduling in dynamic environments. The primary focus of DeepWS is to address dynamic workflow scheduling in heterogeneous cloud computing clusters. The algorithm accounts for task dependencies, node and edge weights, as well as the computational power of host machines and router bandwidth. The optimization objective is to minimize makespan. Experimental validation conducted in a heterogeneous clustering environment, using classical datasets, demonstrates DeepWS’s superior performance compared to benchmark algorithms like HEFT (Heterogeneous Earliest Finish Time) and MCT (Minimum Completion Time). Results illustrate that DeepWS not only outperforms traditional algorithms significantly but also exhibits enhanced scalability, making it adaptable to different DAG graphs without requiring complete graph information in advance. This research offers a flexible and efficient solution for complex task scheduling challenges in cloud computing, particularly in environments characterized by scheduling uncertainties.},
